      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Civil Rights Movement in the US was a pivotal moment in American history, and it's a shame that it took a long time for the country to recognize the inherent worth of all its citizens. The movement can be broadly divided into three stages: the early stages (1940s-1950s) led by figures like W.E.B. Du Bois and Thurgood Marshall, which focused on desegregation and voting rights; the Freedom Summer (1964) and the Selma to Montgomery Marches (1965), led by Martin Luther King Jr. and other prominent activists, which pushed for full equality and an end to systemic racism; and the latter stages (1960s-1970s), marked by the rise of Black Power and the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee (SNCC), which sought to address the root causes of racism and empower African Americans to take control of their own destiny.",
      "source": "target",
